{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17604433","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17604433"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T12:53:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T12:53:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15831"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15831","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15831"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.08,0.71,0.04,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8522"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113949"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8522","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8522"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15831"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95964"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"8648"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20457"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20460"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20513"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113949","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/113949"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring embryological development, the primitive gut tube is divided into three main segments based on their blood supply.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following correctly describes the anatomical extent of the foregut?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oropharynx to jejunum","Stomach to duodenojejunal flexure","Oropharynx to second part of duodenum","Pharynx to gastro-oesophageal junction","Oesophagus to pylorus of stomach"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primitive gut tube develops into the gastrointestinal tract and is divided into three segments based on their blood supply. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eoropharynx to second part of duodenum\u003C/strong\u003E correctly describes the extent of the foregut, which is supplied by the coeliac artery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eoropharynx to jejunum\u003C/strong\u003E extends too far distally beyond the foregut boundary. The \u003Cstrong\u003Estomach to duodenojejunal flexure\u003C/strong\u003E does not include the oesophagus and extends into midgut territory. The \u003Cstrong\u003Epharynx to gastro-oesophageal junction\u003C/strong\u003E does not include the duodenum, which is part of the foregut. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eoesophagus to pylorus of stomach\u003C/strong\u003E excludes both the oropharynx and the duodenum, which are integral components of the foregut. The midgut extends from the entry of the bile duct to the distal third of the transverse colon and is supplied by the superior mesenteric artery. The hindgut extends from the distal third of the transverse colon to the upper part of the anal canal and is supplied by the inferior mesenteric artery.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The foregut extends from the oropharynx to the duodenum at the entry of the bile duct","The midgut extends from the duodenum at the entry of the bile duct to the distal third of the transverse colon","The hindgut extends from the distal third of the transverse colon to the upper part of the anal canal"],"references":["Sadler TW. Langman\u0027s Medical Embryology: Wolters Kluwer; 2015."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95964"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15831"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id"